com.bluegosling.collections.tries

Interface Componentizer<T,U>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of the composite object
    U - the type of the component (sub-object)
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    BitConverter<T>
    Functional Interface:
    This is a functional interface and can therefore be used as the assignment target for a lambda expression or method reference.

    @FunctionalInterface
public interface Componentizer<T,U>
    An interface used to break a composite object up into its constituent components.

    • Method Summary

      All Methods Static Methods Instance Methods Abstract Methods Default Methods 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      static Componentizer<CharSequence,Character> forCharSequence()
      Returns a componentizer that breaks any CharSequence (for example, a String) into its component characters.
      static Componentizer<CharSequence,Integer> forCodePointSequence()
      Returns a componentizer that breaks any CharSequence (for example, a String) into its component unicode code points.
      Iterable<U> getComponents(T t)
      Breaks the specified object into a sequence of components.

    • Method Detail

      • getComponents

        Iterable<U> getComponents(T t)
        Breaks the specified object into a sequence of components.
        Parameters:
        t - the composite object
        Returns:
        the object's sequence of components

      • forCharSequence

        static Componentizer<CharSequence,Character> forCharSequence()
        Returns a componentizer that breaks any CharSequence (for example, a String) into its component characters. Any surrogate pairs remain uninterpreted, resulting in two adjacent values in the components.
        Returns:
        a componentizer that breaks up CharSequences into characters.

      • forCodePointSequence

        static Componentizer<CharSequence,Integer> forCodePointSequence()
        Returns a componentizer that breaks any CharSequence (for example, a String) into its component unicode code points. Unlike forCharSequence(), surrogate pairs are interpreted and combined, as if by Character.toCodePoint(char, char). Non-surrogate pairs and other characters are zero-extended to the code point width.
        Returns:
        a componentizer that breaks up CharSequences into characters.
